,{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a distributed race condition: both processes check 'is migration X applied?' nearly simultaneously, find nothing, and both try to apply it. Mocks hide this entirely. Even Integration tests with async concurrency in a single process risk missing OS process scheduling edge cases. The real failure mode requires actual OS process separation and concurrent database access. Separate Node.js processes hitting the same PostgreSQL instance is the minimum to reliably catch such races.","test_description":"Spawn two concurrent Node.js processes, each running the migration runner against the same PostgreSQL database containing the same set of migration files. Coordinate their start times to maximize race condition likelihood (e.g., both reach the 'check if applied' step before either commits). Monitor database connection activity. Verify: each migration is applied exactly once (no duplicate records in _migrations), no migration succeeds in both processes, and both processes complete without conflict errors.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"At System level with actual OS process concurrency against a shared database, any failure to serialize migration application would be caught. However, this test depends critically on proper synchronization to trigger the race; if sync is weak, the race might not always reproduce.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"A mock with _migrations pre-existing would pass even if the runner crashes when trying to insert into a non-existent table. Only a truly fresh database reveals whether the runner correctly creates _migrations before attempting to record the first migration.","test_description":"Obtain a fresh PostgreSQL database with no existing _migrations table (or use a test DB that starts empty). Run the migration runner with a set of migration files. Verify the _migrations table is created, verify the first migration record is successfully inserted, and verify all subsequent migrations are properly tracked in _migrations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"At Integration level with a fresh database, any failure to create the table before use would manifest immediately as an INSERT error. The initialization order guarantee is enforceable by the test.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13467,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13467},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"efb0063e-2d1b-4418-a438-b3ca91171cd3","uuid":"1b3e9bf4-addb-4e59-972d-4277c41be88f"}
